{
  "title": "Deep Dive: _warnings Standard Library Module in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This explainer provides an in-depth look at the _warnings standard library module, its enhancements, and new features introduced in Python 3.12+.",
  "key_points": [
    "_warnings offers a powerful way to control and manage warnings within your codebase",
    "_warnings supports custom filters for handling specific warning categories",
    "New filter functions like `register` and `unregister` allow for dynamic registration of custom filters in Python 3.12+",
    "_warnings can now generate color-coded output when using the rich library",
    "The new `formatwarning` function allows for easy customization of warning messages"
  ],
  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "import warnings\nwith warnings.catch_warnings(record=True) as w:\n    warnings.simplefilter('error')\n    # Some code that generates a warning\n    for warn in w:\n        print(warn.message)"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "import _warnings\n_warnings.formatwarning = my_custom_format_function"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from rich import print\nfrom _warnings import warn\nwarn(Warning, 'A custom warning')"
    }
  ],
  "version_notes": [
    "Python 3.12 introduced dynamic registration of filters with `register` and `unregister` functions",
    "Color-coded output is available when using the rich library in Python 3.12+"
  ],
  "caveats": [
    "_warnings filters are applied to all modules loaded during the lifetime of the interpreter, not just the one where they're defined.",
    "The `_warnings` module should be used with caution as modifying warning behavior may impact the stability or readability of your codebase"
  ]
